			<div class="content" id="post-content-1393768">
									

<p>I'm confused by this tale, a lot.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Spoilers!&nbsp;Spoilers&nbsp;abound!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Spoilers!&nbsp;Spoilers&nbsp;abound!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>He is right in that O5 are 001. But the rest is not the distraction. The briefcase is. The part about O5 requiring new people once in a while - that part was true. The briefcase was the final test. There isn't really anything there. If he didn't run, he'd become one of them, whatever that means. And now he is just overestimating his ability to evade the Foundation. Just like Howey thought that there was no cameras, he now thinks that there is no security. And once he reaches the city, it will all be over.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>At least that's what I <em>think</em> happens in this tale's canon. Which, while quite interesting, won't be joining my head-canon any time soon.</p>
<p>Of-course, I could be completely off with my interpretation.</p>

							</div>

								
					
