<p>I absolutely bloody love this. Upvoted when I reached part 2, then wanted to upvote again at several different places. exp(Hell yes!)</p>
<p>That said.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>1) I don't particularly think he's right - the thing about a cell one doesn't want to leave is a tempting line of thought, but then, people do get promoted into O5 ranks&#8230; besides given the Foundation's structure, the question is sort of, what can't they do. Of course there's the whole line of thought that not wanting to do something is really equivalent to not being able to, but well, who knows. My ideas about the Foundation are different.<br />
2) Not really. Thing is, I think the whole charade was a win-win sort of a gambit. It appeared he might do this kind of thing at some time, but he was capable enough to be worth keeping&#8230; hence. either try triggering him in conditions where it's unlikely he'll succeed at fucking up, or, if by some miraculous chance he doesn't trigger and the evaluation was wrong, keeping him as level 4 staff is a good idea anyways.<br />
tl;dr I expect whatever CIA office he walks into to contain a few guys with Class A amnesiacs at hand. Or a gun.</p>
</div>
